375–1437","1385–1416":"1385–1416","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1437":"1437","Abt 1350":"about 1350","1324":"1324","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1416":"1416","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is probably derived from the surname. In England this surname is found mainly in the West Midlands; it has also spread into Wales. In Ireland this form is common in Ulster; MacLysaght records that it was taken there from England in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Memory","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Mowbray was born about 1350, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with Hugh de Waterton. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1350–Deceased":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1385–1416":"1385–1416","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1437":"1437","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1324":"1324","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1416":"1416","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1350–Deceased":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1385–1416":"1385–1416","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1437":"1437","Abt 1350":"noin 1350","1324":"1324","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1416":"1416","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1350–Deceased":"environ 1350–Décédée","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1385–1416":"1385–1416","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1437":"1437","Abt 1350":"environ 1350","1324":"1324","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1416":"1416","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ellen Mowbray est née environ 1350, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 filles avec Hugh de Waterton. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"Abt 1350–Deceased":"um 1350–Verstorben","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1385–1416":"1385–1416","1350–Female":"1350–Verstorben","1437":"1437","Abt 1350":